1
00:00:04,280 --> 00:00:09,074
If we want to look at the relationship between two categorical variables,

2
00:00:09,074 --> 00:00:12,720
then we have to go beyond simple positional encodings.

3
00:00:12,720 --> 00:00:14,475
Earlier in this lesson,

4
00:00:14,475 --> 00:00:19,635
you saw how heat maps depict a 2D histogram across two numeric variables.

5
00:00:19,635 --> 00:00:23,535
A similar strategy can be used for two categorical variables,

6
00:00:23,535 --> 00:00:26,400
analogous to creating a 2D bar chart.

7
00:00:26,400 --> 00:00:31,555
However, if we want to avoid the imprecision of using color to encode numbers,

8
00:00:31,555 --> 00:00:35,345
then the standard plot choice is the clustered bar chart.

9
00:00:35,345 --> 00:00:39,860
A clustered bar chart starts out the same as the univariate bar chart with

10
00:00:39,860 --> 00:00:44,810
the levels of one variable on the x-axis and counts to be plotted on the y-axis.

11
00:00:44,810 --> 00:00:49,220
However, instead of just one bar being plotted at each exposition,

12
00:00:49,220 --> 00:00:51,290
we instead have multiple bars,

13
00:00:51,290 --> 00:00:55,265
one for each level of the second variable we want to plot.

14
00:00:55,265 --> 00:00:59,630
Typically, we apply a color or texture encoding to each bar

15
00:00:59,630 --> 00:01:04,295
in each cluster to distinguish between the levels of the second variable.

16
00:01:04,295 --> 00:01:08,810
Thus, the counts depicted by the height of each bar are associated with

17
00:01:08,810 --> 00:01:14,060
the general exposition for the first variable and the color for the second variable.

18
00:01:14,060 --> 00:01:16,970
This correspondence is easier to see when we

19
00:01:16,970 --> 00:01:19,895
put the heat map next to the clustered bar chart.

20
00:01:19,895 --> 00:01:22,280
Comparing the two visualizations,

21
00:01:22,280 --> 00:01:25,670
you can see the increased precision and understanding the ranking and

22
00:01:25,670 --> 00:01:31,050
differences in frequency counts when you look at the bar chart compared to the heat map.

